If you prefer a more vim-like workflow (i.e. jumping in and out of your editor from your shell), a good solution is to fire up emacs in daemon mode to run in the background, and then connect to it using emacsclient.<p>I automatically run<p><pre><code>  emacsclient --daemon
</code></pre>
when my OS boots up.<p>In my .zshrc and .bashrc files, I use the aliases<p><pre><code>  alias e=&#x27;emacsclient -t&#x27;
  alias vi=&#x27;emacsclient -t&#x27;
</code></pre>
to give me quick access to emacs from the shell.<p>I&#x27;m not sure if this addresses your problems entirely, but it does keep you from having to deal with all of the crap that loads on startup.
